The government wants to curb the torture of "witches", and has published a pamphlet
Women accused of witchcraft in Burkina Faso have several characteristics in common.
They are more of the older generation, cannot work for health reasons, are single and have no children.
The one who becomes a witch is sent into isolation so she doesn't threaten the rest of the village.
"A man's fate is very rare".
"Even young, healthy women don't give up because they are helping with work and childbirth", says a nun who cares for more than 100 women expelled by her community in a special house in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual "social measure".
She's published a pamphlet of information to help curb the witch hunt.
There's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of Burkinabe adults cannot read", notes the newspaper Die Standard, a literary magazine.
Charges of witchcraft are common in other African lands as well.
In Ghana, which borders Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week after being tortured, doused in kerosene and set on fire by three women and two men.
The case was reported by the BBC's server.
The perpetrators claim it was an accident.
According to their version, the woman was burned by an oil used for ritual anointing.
It was said to have flown after a group tried to "exorcise an evil spirit" from a woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of their educational attainment.
Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "Soul-eaters have always been a danger".
While the government is trying to curb the witch hunt in Burkina Faso, the president himself participated in the Gambia witch hunt last year.
"After the death of his aunt, Gambian President Jammeh launched a massive witch hunt, allegedly to have been responsible for her death and to have used black magic to try to kill the president himself".
"He enlisted the help of shamans from nearby Guinea, who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president's personal bodyguards, forcibly took randomly selected men and women from Gambian villages to the president's farm in Kanilai", said Amnesty International in a report.
At the farm, the prisoners were forced to drink a herbal potion with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two prisoners did not survive their stay at the farm.
After international pressure, nearly a thousand prisoners were eventually released.
