The office is a nursery, architects understand
The Avriopoint administration building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
What you would not expect is a mini-school with all the makings - colorful walls, fancy furniture, a pile of toys, and even a miniature outdoor playground.
Since October last year, it's been open to the children of Arch.Design employees.
The architectural design company Arch.Design, whose studios have produced a number of important Brno buildings, had been planning for a space for its corporate mini-school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
She employs nearly 90 people, mostly baby boomers, and she was concerned that women designers and architects could get back to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of reduced shifts, daycare is a benefit that Arch.Design offers its employees as part of its social program.
Women in construction and architecture are able to combine demanding work with childcare.
The idea of the mini-school was conceived by the Arch.Design staff themselves and with the support of the management, they managed to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-school is financed from the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the Czech State Budget.
Thanks to grant funding (grant of CZK 2.8 million), they were able to buy equipment and equip qualified staff and operate for two years.
After the financial support (2 years) has been exhausted, Arch.Design is obliged to run the mini-school at its own expense for 3 years.
The project took a year to prepare and was substantially assisted by Economy Rating in applying for the grant.
The childcare is provided by qualified staff, the children are looked after by a nurse and a primary school teacher throughout the day, so that children can attend the nursery without age restrictions, although most of them are over 3 years old.
Because it is a "mini-school", only five children can attend at a time, but more may be added during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the nursery regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although the education and care is individual, the curriculum in the mini-school is comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
Children not only play here, but they also receive quality education - from basic knowledge to preparation for school, including English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys, with games, but also with a computer that the children can use.
The presence of young children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive atmosphere.
Parents can check on their child at any time and stressful situations with delayed pickups from daycare centers far from the parents' workplace are eliminated.
Parents thus use their working hours more productively.
No wonder an employee-employer relationship is naturally formed.
Arch.Design was thus ranked among the Czech companies offering a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, is family-friendly and through this program has strengthened personnel marketing.
A house made of bones is still fascinating after 100 years.
The roof looks like an ancient lizard's back, the staircase resembles a dinosaur's spine, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
Such is the Casa Batlló in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
The house has earned the nickname "The Bone House" from the locals because of its organic shapes.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade resembling a scales and omnipresent soft curves, all are typical of Antoni Gaudí's secesi.
The house's facade is marked by dreamlike lines, soft colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
When you look closely, you see geometry, rhythm, and a well-thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house is made even more dramatic, illuminated to enhance the impression of the brilliance of the colors.
The warping and the twisting of shapes are equally present in interiors.
The wood in the waves replicates window frames, railings, door trimmings, blinds, and rafters.
The Batlló house, which stands in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, is a reconstruction of the 1877 house by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaudi's idea for an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
The stately home of Casa Batlló, but Antoni Gaudí did not design it himself.
He collaborated with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his design board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the property owner and the use of mosaic on the facade were created.
A number of other designers and artists worked on the facade.
The joint work on the Casa Batlló project started a successful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá and the Güell Park, which houses other works by Gaudí.
The house earned the nickname "the House of Bones" from the locals soon after its completion, thanks to its organic shapes.
Others have called it "the whistling house" because of its unique mechanism for opening windows.
It is also said that on the top of the building is the sword of St George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motives also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a central heating system for the house, unique for its time, with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Bizarre as it may seem, they have a 45-degree tilt.
Gaudí was not bound by the building regulations of the time.
At the beginning of the construction, although he obtained a building permit from the city, the data he gave about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, when the city council was shocked by the result and asked for a correction.
For example, the council was concerned that the construction interfered with the pillars and the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, no corrective action was ever taken: only 15 days after the City Council's appeal, Josep Batlló applied for (and was granted) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner moved into the lower floors himself.
The second floor gallery was the social hall, and the third floor was the bedroom and private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building is divided by a staircase that leads up to the roof terrace itself.
The key elements of the reconstruction were the elimination of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The public area can be completely connected by opening the living room doors, and the larger company can communicate with each other comfortably, without at the same time retaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
The Gaudí-designed house has a new facade, an unconventional roof, and two additional floors.
Also impressive is Gaudi's play with light, with the blue and white glazed tiles that line the inner courtyard, and with the lights.
The two-color play provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
All they had to do was bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs the sun's rays.
Casa Batlló, which was designated a Unesco World Heritage Site in 2005, is open to the public.
On the first floor of the house, the most spacious and most ostentatious apartment is open to the public.
The owners decided to do this in 2002, to celebrate the 150th anniversary of the famous creator's birth.
They persisted in the inspection, finding it to be a very profitable enterprise, and further expanded the inspection to the common and loft areas, including the roof terrace.
The entrance fee is certainly not insignificant, at 16.50 euros, and students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders enjoy a twenty-percent discount.
The sum is far more than the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
