People-watching devices are becoming more and more popular with parents looking to watch their children.
Fear of having a child of their own is leading more and more people to the idea of GPS surveillance.
A system originally designed to track cars can also track people's movements, helping in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anicka Janatková.
The device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it may be as big as a watch.
Many people were alarmed by the case of Miss Anička's disappearance and began to look for ways to protect their children.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying, but it is just another way to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment to the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases, there may be abuse of such devices, such as putting them in a bag for someone who does not know, but we have not seen such a case".
"Most of the time, it's really something that customers buy for security reasons", Pilin added.
He says that the child should always know the purpose of the "box" and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bochkov points out that if a child does not want to wear something like this, he simply gets rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in deliberately losing things when they don't want to be controlled".
"In the past, parents were very excited about mobile phones, which can be turned off just like these tracking devices", says Bočková.
She also said that it was questionable whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
"In the case of a planned abduction, the perpetrator will almost always ensure that the child has no electronics that could reveal his or her location".
"Now it's the phone".
"When surveillance devices begin to proliferate, they will be sought out, as their sale will surely be boosted by massive advertising".
"In that case, the criminals will always be one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, he admits that such a device can help in the case of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, a company that offers surveillance services for both cars and people, even if the surveillance device is destroyed immediately after an attack, its presence can help.
'The device may be set to periodically transmit the position after a certain period.'
"In the event of damage, at least the last known location of the person concerned will be available".
"The more expensive devices have built-in inclinometers, so even if a person slips and stays still, the device will send an instant alert with a location", says Čech.
He believes that a similar service can be provided by a navigation-enabled smartphone, which can be accessed by downloading special software.
The problem with current tracking devices is that they're either match-box-sized trailers or smaller cell phones.
They're always in danger of losing them.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, this is why they are now testing a device that looks like a standard digital watch.
"This will have the biggest advantage in that an attacker may not even know the tracking device".
"Nebo will only recognize them after a while and that can give the police extra time", he adds.
Whether the tracking devices evolve into bracelets or necklaces, they'll still use the same technology used to patrol cars.
It is a combination of GPS positioning (used in conventional car navigation) and a mobile phone function that reports the current position of the vehicle.
The army has fire-strings to envelop the Czech Republic, but they'll only last two years.
The Czech army has purchased 445 kilometers of detonation cords.
Last year, the Department of Defense delivered 224 kilometers of rope to the warehouse.
The army has enough for 225 years.
The problem is, the life of the cord is two years, four at the most.
The army bought the firing line from the STV Group, a.s. for 40 million crowns.
The General Staff, justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of MF DNES match ropes, wrote that the soldiers use 60 kilometers of matches per year during training.
However, military fire engineers' calculations, which MF DNES has consulted, show that all generals, army command officers, secretaries or cleaners would also have to undergo very intensive fire engineer training every year.
Minister of Defense Alexander Vondra and the commander of the army Vlastimil Picka are not exempt.
