Longer fingers than rings means less risk of cancer
Men with a longer index finger than a ring finger are at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
That's the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
It could be related to the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that relative finger length can serve as a simple prostate cancer risk test, especially for men up to 60", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, especially when combined with genetic risk or other risk factors such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and over 3,000 healthy men in parallel.
More than half of the study participants had an index finger on their right hand shorter than a ring finger.
They had the same risk of prostate cancer as the 19% of men with the same finger length.
However, for those with index fingers longer than their ring fingers, the risk dropped by 33 percent, and for men in their 60's, the drop was as high as 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed during the prenatal period - seems to reflect the different levels of sex hormones that the baby is exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone is the same as a longer index finger.
Earlier research has shown that testosterone is the main driver of prostate cancer growth.
Professor Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Czech Academy of Sciences, told the Czech National Research Council that he was not familiar with the study but that he did not think that the link between finger length and cancer had been "fully established".
