Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is support for private enterprise.
Criminal activity is more of a concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is considered by many regions to be more influential than the United States.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
As the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
Two related things dominate this year's survey, which was conducted in September and early October.
The first is that Latin America is in a pretty cheerful mood.
The second is to increase stability in attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy was recovering from a deep decline in output last year.
But only about half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are Democrats, which is below the regional average (see Chart 2).
Some 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year but a big increase from 25% in 2001 (Graph 3).
Around 34% said they trusted the parliament in their country and 45% trusted the government, again the same figures as last year, but a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, democracy in Latin America was undermined by an economic crisis.
The support was generated during the global financial crisis, probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social safety net has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latinos living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again to 32% this year.)
However, mood varies widely from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and the violent crime situation worsened.
For only the second time since surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime as the most important problem than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Around 31% say that they or their close relatives have been victims of crime in the past year, but this is down from the 38% figure of last year and also the lowest number since 1995.
The stronger economic performance is reflected in the growing support for private enterprise and market economies: some 71% of respondents across the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will enable their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela share the same view (and 80% support private enterprise there), despite their leftist president Hugo Chávez's expropriation of many private companies.
Brazil is the country that leads the field, as mentioned by 19% of respondents (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, up from 11% last year)
However, the United States is considered the most influential respondent country in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
