Microbes resistant to arsenic are increasing the possibility of new forms of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the search for new life forms on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth, and they say it's a sign that life has possibilities beyond the main elements that have been considered fundamental.
"This organism has a dual capacity".
"It can grow on either phosphorus or arsenic".
"This is a very strange finding, but it is not evidence of any form of truly 'alien' life", commented Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appeared Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
For a long time, the six basic elements that were considered essential to life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur - were considered to be the most important.
However, scientists have found that bacteria discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue growing after arsenic is replaced by phosphorus.
"It's amazing to see what's still possible", said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
The find is important for the search for life beyond Earth, because researchers must be able to recognize life and know what life might look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report on this new find published for discussion, which did not disclose the details of the find, has sparked widespread speculation online that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It's not like that.
The discovery "suggests that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements that drive biochemistry and that the set of elements we consider 'standard' may not be as absolutely necessary for life", explained Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, Great Britain.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element with another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure", added Cockell.
It wasn't a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the Astrobiology Institute at NASA, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she thought that a microbe exposed to both elements might be able to substitute for each other.
"Arsenic is toxic primarily because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus".
"As a result, organisms have great difficulty separating these elements from one another".
"However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work like phosphorus, but when it enters the body, it starts working in biochemical processes", Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which the bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better with phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic substitution, it raises the possibility that arsenic-using life forms may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on other planets or moons where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, a graduate assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea of arsenic being replaced by phosphorus is not new, but that no example has ever been found to prove this.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, so scientists speculated that it might have been used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways of creating life, not just the way it formed in the early Earth", said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
