Can courtesy cross the abyss?
After a campaign that was notable for its offensiveness and negativity, a small amount of civility has emerged in Washington this week.
Is this the first flurry of real cooperation between the two political parties, or merely an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan fighting in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and the House leaders did not yield any major findings on the key issues that must be discussed during the session.
But in any case, it was a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides and the definition of their shared responsibilities, rather than another empty episode of partisan infighting.
Wednesday's public meeting of the President's deficit-control commission was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close cooperation over several months has built a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still divides the members.
And it's not easy to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both parties are now in a trial period - probing each other's signs of collegiality and compromise, as they try to gauge the limits of public opinion and voter tolerance for renewed partisan warfare.
Therefore, the Tuesday meeting and its subsequent evaluation by the participants was conducted with minimal demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too wide and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the relationship that has prevailed here for the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, spending, health care, or rights, the two sides are miles apart.
However, the November election prepared Washington at least quickly.
"There is no question that regulatory issues have changed", said Pete Wehner, Bush's administrator, now at the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"They are inevitable after the election.
The election stirred up party emotions and then they went quiet.
It's good".
On a few issues, especially those that are scheduled to be discussed at the session, Republicans and Democrats have little chance of finding a solution.
Bush's tax cuts expired at the end of the year, and no one is taking them for granted.
Both sides want to find a way to protect some or all of them, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a likely compromise on unemployment benefits only because Republicans can't look at how they support tax cuts for the wealthy while denying unemployment benefits to the unemployed.
After the White House meeting on Tuesday, there is already greater optimism about a possible agreement on these issues, along with the ratification of a new initial treaty.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution points out that successful cooperation on critical issues will not necessarily lead to a bipartisan relationship when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Rather, it is a likely period of inconsistency, or even inevitable, he said.
"After the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations", he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism - which is widespread - that politeness leads to real cooperation.
"I look at all events between now and 2012 as a shadow box where the major events will occur in 2012", he said.
The reasons are largely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the White House and the Tea Party voters who helped create it.
Republican leaders now face the danger of exaggeration, knowing that they must live up to their promises and must cut government spending and repeal the new health care law.
These supporters' lines are clear in the initial reactions to the deficit recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the toughest jobs in Washington and are, in their view, supposed to bring the issue of the deficit to the public agenda in ways that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to present their plan as a formal recommendation, and they are fighting to get as close to that number as possible.
The biggest opposition is among elected officials on the jury, who suggest that when it comes to financial issues, at least today, we have little basis or will to compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House and congressional Republicans.
The first will begin next year in the form of a bipartisan conflict, with the Republicans challenging Obama over budget, tax and health care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What causes the shift?
The public opinion.
There is ample evidence that despite the partisan nature of the last election, most Americans continue to want to see two parties working together.
If it could be headed for a standoff, as it was in 1995, then both sides will be watching closely for public reactions.
Anyone threatened with a vote cut is likely to change course and seek a compromise.
That may be an optimistic view.
There is a greater degree of partisanship and bias today than there was in the mid-1990s, and it appears that there is a greater ideological gap between Obama and the House Republicans than there was between the Republicans and Bill Clinton.
At the same time, activists on both sides see 2010 as a prelude to the more important elections in 2012.
Given this reality, the politeness that has emerged this week would be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take a lot of effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
