The software suggests improvements in vehicles in real time.
Since Red Bull's entry into Formula One in 2004, its history in this extraordinary world of speed has been one of surprise and success.
At first, no one took the prospects of this new team too seriously, and despite the recent upward trend, everyone was betting on Fernando Alonso's Ferrari to triumph.
Without wanting to diminish the riding skills of the champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, or the possibilities of the Renault engine that powers his car, a legend was born in the world of Formula One - the "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens put in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
In reality, it is a powerful software simulation of gaits that the German firm launched in 2007 for purposes far removed from motor sport.
The so-called PLM, this powerful software tool, has been used to design assembly lines in manufacturing plants around the world, in power plants and for high-precision machines.
Its aim is to faithfully reproduce the product or simulate the process before it is actually created, thereby avoiding unnecessary errors and expenses.
PLM has facilitated the development of the Canon camera, the Sukhoi aircraft, and the most famous Nissan commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this software device allowed the Red Bull team to make "in a few hours, in near real time" modifications and improvements that would otherwise be detected during races and tests.
Russwurm says that in 1992, the stables employed an average of 10 technicians, who were able to perform a maximum of three or four improvements in a single season.
The Red Bull team today has 180 young, highly qualified professionals equipped with powerful information technology, who analyse and design every type of modification of racing vehicles.
The Siemens executive explained that the PLM software is able to analyse and improve all the elements of Red Bull racing cars, with the exception of the engine, for which Renault is fully responsible.
Modifications are being made to the materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features.
Changes can be made from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced manufacturing systems using laser and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit to this technical expense is the $40 million, the maximum that any Formula One team can spend in any season to improve its competitiveness.
