Let it be said in advance that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which is at odds with the idea of keeping to old traditions that a large part of the other members hold.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also Austria or the Netherlands, while the southern countries would leave the currency area.
The second is the return to the brand - although it may seem like sci-fi now, this version has a broad public support, approaching 50% of the population.
A third option is the German proposal to rework the euro with greater macroeconomic surveillance, fiscal austerity, fines for failing states, possible deferrals of payments for some of them, and the extension of possible regulatory costs to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is no room for distortions now.
First, when the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission instigated deficits in 2009, the German government pulled out of the constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of the contradiction between what Germany considered to be the right thing (fiscal austerity plans and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The second was shown by this central European country when Merkel painfully delayed the decision on the Greek bailout.
