In any event, the debate revolves around whether this type of conduct, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is to say whether these acts are circumventing the law; they are in fact actions respecting the sporting rules, the meaning of which, of course, seems to be circumvented.
It's about the damage that this kind of behavior does to the spirit of the sport.
One of the requirements of sportsmanship is the physical integrity of the opposing players, which in these cases has not been violated, meaning that there has been no violent play.
Another of these features of fair play is to avoid giving players an advantage over the opposing team by committing an offense - which did not happen here.
So the paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that there was no what we normally characterise as trickery or circumvention of the law, no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but rather this behaviour had to be as visible as possible in order to receive punishment.
They waited and they were happy to be punished.
The next question is, What advantage will the guilty party of their willful transgression have?
It must be noted that the opponent is not put at a disadvantage and that he does not benefit from the current match, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And that's not a useful strategy for the next game either, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardise their participation in future matches.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, so at first glance the team can be eliminated, and yet by doing this, the players will collect their punishment and move to the second round of cards, in which elimination is one less card than in the first round.
So as the rounds continue, it's not clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the spirit of sport, which is to make strategic decisions that allow maximum benefit to be gained within the rules.
In the case we are dealing with, the players did not have the goal of avoiding the penalty (which would be a clear case of circumvention), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without avoiding punishment or running away from it.
While the line between wit and circumvention is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case, it was clearly wit.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because there were two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the instructions to provoke them were transmitted from the management.
The violation of sporting principles by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
