The United States is changing its visa policy
People will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres before the interview at the Consular Section; costs will be lower and waiting times will be shortened.
As of 10 January 2011, the visa application process at the Embassies and Consulates of the United States of America will change.
The new procedure will require most applicants to contact the Visa Applicants Service Centres (ASC) before the interview at the Consular Section.
The ASC personnel will collect the applicant's biometric information and it will be evaluated by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The overall cost of processing a visa will be lower, with no longer having to pay a fee for arranging an appointment, another for processing the application and another for delivering the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the amount corresponding to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with applications (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will simply contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
As biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who require a second interview appointment at the Consular Section will spend less time there than in the past.
Also, those who apply for visas at the consulates in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay an additional $26 service fee.
The visa application form is sent to the visa office of the issuing country.
