The Quebec consumer has very little confidence in sustainable development actors, but also in 'neutral' brands and environmental certifications to guide his product choices.
The worst part is that even though we buy into a media universe that urges us to be more socially responsible in our consumption, this media universe bemoans the lack of credible information, the failure to comply with obligations that even qualifies as a brake on its commitment, according to the Responsible Consumption Barometer, whose first article was published yesterday.
Even though the consumption of so-called socially responsible products increased in 2010, Quebecers who try to sell them still don't have much faith in them.
In fact, two-thirds of us say that we don't trust companies' environmental promises, simply because the green advertising of companies is measured by a measuring tool developed by the Responsible Consumption Observatory at the University of Sherbrooke.
