Similarly, the debate on the issue is taken seriously by only 14.6% of Quebecers.
However, responsible consumption information seems to be the primary way of stimulating this aspect of consumption, which is currently being revived by almost a third of Quebec consumers.
Indeed, the vacuum and the questionable nature of the information would dampen the enthusiasm of 46% of consumers.
This is the second brake that Barometer has identified, after the higher price of these products.
After all, a third of Quebecers are skeptical of the green products or services we're looking to pass through our hands.
On the other hand, in 2010, almost half of consumers were willing to change their habits and in particular to change the brand of one or more products in response to their beliefs.
A full 61% of them preferred to shop at local merchants and preferred to buy food grown in their region, according to Barometer.
More "green" and responsible - the Responsible Consumption Index reached 64 out of a maximum of 100 for this year - Homo consumus Québec likes to present itself as the recycling king, seeking to minimize its impact on the environment by caring for the protection of animals.
