The World Plan for the Restoration of Lighting
The UN yesterday in Cancun proposed a plan to renovate residential, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve GHG reductions, which is almost one third of the additional limit needed to stabilize the planet's climate from now to 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the process of being developed into large concrete projects that the UN wants to push through in Cancun to compensate for the absence of hard-to-achieve reduction commitments by industrialised countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if we replace incandescent light bulbs, which still monopolise 50 to 70 percent of the market, with fluorescent or, better yet, LED light bulbs, a substantial amount of the 1.8 billion tons of GHG emissions on the planet caused by lighting would be eliminated.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That's equivalent to 70% of the emissions from the entire car fleet on the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, major countries with significant emissions, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, joined voluntary reduction plans that would reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will take another 5 Gt to stabilize global warming to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 to rule out that it doesn't get out of control.
In a burning light bulb, 95% of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5% is produced by light.
With fluocompact light bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with the new LED light bulbs, we'll reduce that consumption by half.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs that Philips is rolling out this week - the company was reportedly involved in a UN study - have an estimated lifespan of 25,000 hours and use 80% less energy than a light bulb, giving us a sense of the potential savings with a replacement plan that would apply in 100 countries.
All of these new bulbs can also work with the rheostats and emit less heat.
And they contain no mercury.
Several experts have raised concerns about fluorocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be sorted as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless manufacturers set up collection sites.
However, the report notes, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluorescent bulb but rather thermal coal power plants, which release much of the mercury needed to produce electricity that is wasted in the burning bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants put 25,000 tons of mercury into circulation each year.
The report also details the benefits that each country would derive from this international program.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year in electricity and 8 million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost $2.5 billion to build.
