The unemployment rate in France remains stable in the third quarter.
The International Labour Office (ILO) unemployment rate in France remained stable at 9.3% in metropolitan France (9.7% including the overseas regions), according to provisional seasonally adjusted data (CVS) published by INSEE on Thursday.
The unemployment rate has stabilized at 2.631 million in the metropolitan area.
The second quarter figures were confirmed at 9.3% of the active population in the metropolitan area and 9.7% including the overseas regions.
In one year, the unemployment rate increases by 0.1 percentage point.
In the wider context, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France were not working in the third quarter but would like to work, regardless of whether they are available to work in two weeks' time and regardless of whether they are looking for work or not.
The situation of young people in the labour market today was further exacerbated by a new increase in the unemployment rate, which reached 24.2% in metropolitan France (+0.9 points in three months, +0.5 points in one year) and 25% including the overseas regions.
In the third quarter, according to the International Labour Office, there were 637,000 unemployed young people aged 15 to 24.
As for the elderly, they recorded a slight increase in unemployment in metropolitan France to 6.4% in metropolitan France (+0.2 points in three months, as well as in one year), i.e. 482 000 people aged 50 and over and 6.6% including overseas regions.
Only the population aged 25-49 recorded the benefit of unemployment stability at 8.3% in metropolitan France (-0.1 points in three months, +0.1 points in one year) and 8.8% in the whole of France.
Insee has not published the monthly unemployment rate since 2006, following a controversy over its calculation method.
Eurostat, the statistical agency of the European Union, on the other hand, continues to produce monthly statistics, reporting on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (including the DOM) in October, after 9.9% in September.
