The vengeful hackers and the sensitive spies
The WikiLeaks case is two-fold.
On the one hand, there is the obvious scandal, a scandal that seems to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's take it one step at a time.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks, it's a confirmation of the fact that every document compiled by the secret service of any nation consists entirely of press cuts.
The Americans' "extraordinary revelations" about Berlusconi's sex life are what everyone has been able to read for months in any newspaper (all but the two Berlusconi's own), and the unflattering caricature of Gaddafi has long been the subject of sketches by cabaret artists.
The rule that classified documents can only consist of news already known is crucial to the dynamics of intelligence, and not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore that specializes in esoteric literature, you will find that each work (of the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Masons) repeats exactly what has already been written in the previous works.
Not only is the author of occult texts reluctant to seek new information (or to know where to look for information about nonexistent things), but those who practice the occult believe only what they already know and what confirms what they have already learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same is true of classified documents.
The informer is a lazy, and lazy (or narrow-minded) head of the secret service (and if he is not, he could be, as I know, an editor at the newspaper Libération), who only believes what he himself admits to be true.
The highly classified information about Berlusconi that the US Embassy sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek had published a week earlier.
So why was there such a fuss about the disclosure of these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultured person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War and since heads of state can make phone calls or fly out to dinner together, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for a few small exercises in representation, have been transformed into espionage centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows full well that it is only out of hypocrisy that it is seemingly ignored.
However, the fact that it is being repeated publicly discredits the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can get the most highly classified information from the most powerful country in the world is a severe, if not a significant, blow to the prestige of this government department.
Scandal affects both the victims and the "perpetrators".
But let's move on from that to the deep truth of what happened.
Back in the days of Orwell, it was possible to grasp all power, like some Big Brother who controlled every move of his people.
Orwell's prophecy has been proven since, with the ability to control every move made by a phone, every transaction made, every hotel visited, every highway used, and so on, the citizen has become a total victim of the crown of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it is now, that even the tombs with the most secret information of the powerful cannot withstand the intervention of a hacker, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker -- chosen as the citizen's avenger -- can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power hold out when it can no longer keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel said that a true secret is a secret without a secret (and a secret without a secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a secret without a secret because it is drawn from public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were secrets without a secret, is to deprive him of all power.
WikiLeaks did not do anything wrong to Sarkozy or Merkel, but they did something big to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this blow to the power so significant?
It is clear that in the future, states will not be able to send sensitive information online - that would be the equivalent of putting it on a billboard on a street corner.
But it is also quite obvious that with current technology it is unrealistic to hope that a phone message can be kept secret.
There's nothing easier than finding out if and when the head of state was on a plane and connected with any of his colleagues.
How can private and sensitive messages be kept secret in the future ?
I know that my prognosis is science fiction at the moment, and therefore fantastic, but I have to imagine government officials who are discreetly transporting the formalities of uncontrollable routes, carrying only those messages that they know by heart or rather conceal valuable information in the heel of their shoes.
The information will be stored in unique copies in key-locked sockets: overall, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving sideways forward, that is, backwards.
One century after the wireless telegraph revolutionised communications, the Internet rehabilitated the telegraph based on telephone wires.
Video cassettes (analogue) allowed moviegoers to shoot a film step by step, moving it back and forth and revealing all the secrets of the montage, whereas CDs (numerical) now allow only chapter jumps, that is, macro-squares.
By express train, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while the plane ride, including the transportation, takes three and a half hours.
It is not surprising, then, that politics and communications technology are reverting to horse-drawn carriages.
One last note.
Other times, the press tried to understand what was going on in the embassy's secret compartment.
Now it's the embassies that are asking for confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France hacked its funding promises
A year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to test the progress of the pledges of developed countries to unlock fast-start financing.
And the great French hacks have been uncovered
In the Cologne Accord, the advanced countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged €7.2 billion for three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million per year).
At the start of COP16, the EU pulled out the big one to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: a report detailing the action of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparent operation, invaluable and appreciated for its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do the same and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has committed EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to deliver its promise of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we look at the details, things are much more complicated.
These funds are 'new and additional' under the Copenhagen Accord to ensure that the increased burden is realised without prejudice to ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the process.
Today, each of you will choose the reference that best suits you.
The European Commission, for example, took 2009 as a reference year: international funding was maintained and it added 150 million for three years of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment terms or with terms at the level of official development assistance.
By contrast, France considers that the funding of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words,there is no reference to previous period expenditure or to the global level of Public Aid for Development (Aide publique au développement).
In particular, the total amount of aid granted by France to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even be reduced) in order to comply with its commitment to finance 'new and additional' measures.
Another crucial element is the division into gifts and loans.
There's no rule yet, and everyone chooses their own way of calculating.
Some, like France, think that 1 euro borrowed equals 1 euro donated.
Obviously, it's hard to prove: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some investments which are profitable (often these are projects linked to the reduction of emissions, based on more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present the one euro we receive as the equivalent of the one euro we give... We should not understand it in terms of our obligations, but as the price of the loan for the creditor country (i.e. the equivalent interest rate).
But France can only provide this justification: it "honors" its commitment of 420 million euros, of which 91,5% is a loan (EUR 389,8 million) and 8,5% a donation (EUR 36,1 million) - see the EU document to verify this for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan on such a scale.
Germany has requested 46% of this, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are keeping their 100% donation commitments.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union puts in 1 euro to meet its pledge, France only puts in 10 cents and considers this effort comparable.
A lovely piece of skittle!
In summary, France's 'fast start' financing is based on two tricks: on the one hand, on the time evolution of the action and, on the other, on the real financial burden.
Although it only spends €36.1 million, it can convince you that it spends €420 million "new and additional" in relation to its promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, both inside the EU (why would member states continue to donate when they can only lend?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The early funding chapter is just a small issue, relatively short-term, in relation to the climate debate series.
But she could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not our case.
Whatever the case, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of early financing.
First of all, France should announce a change in its accounting practices for the years 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respecting its commitments and of fairness and justice towards the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussing the contribution of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): we will not avoid the question of 'additionality' or the way in which loans are accounted for.
France should change its attitude to become as progressive with these deposits as with the others.
So, all hope is placed on the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancún next week.
The surprise announcement of France's fast start and its vision of 'additionality' and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
Alert regarding pesticides that children ingest.
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study released this Wednesday by the Future Generations Association.
The association, which points out that its results "have no significant statistical value in view of the small number of samples analysed, but are characteristic of the problematic area", bought between July and September food normally consumed in four meals and one light meal as a snack per child of about ten years in supermarkets in L'Oise and Paris.
These typical foods, which include the official recommendation - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water a day - as well as sugar confectionery, have been analysed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet is staggering: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are considered to be carcinogenic, possible or probable, and five are considered to be carcinogenic, as well as 37 substances that could act as a disruptor to the endocrine glands (EDs), according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, our research clearly shows that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminants, possibly carcinogenic, and/ or PE is staggering", states the association.
Breakfast butter and milk tea alone contain about ten residues with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
An apple imported from Brazil, cited in the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicidal agent banned in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya included in the lunch, which have been tested for traces of potent insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, ground beef steaks, canned tuna, and even goose and gum were laced with pesticides and other chemicals.
The tap water was tested for nitrates and chloroform.
The salmon steak for dinner was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues found, and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave did not escape analysis.
The study concludes that the final risk to consumers of this 'cocktail of contaminants' is likely to be underestimated.
The Ecological Europe-Green (EE-LV) group proposed a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop "the rise of civilization diseases" in "the face of an emergency".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) examined the state of residue of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 of them in cereals.
